Text: I spent the first half of the week trying to code a solution in Excel only to realized that it didn't quite cut it.
It turns out what I thought to be Excel's strengths, its ability to keep data in sync and visible at all times, do not fit into Milair's workflow.

Since most non-trivial updates need to be approved and old records need to be kept, her needs clearly point to a more robust database that allows for data constraint, step-by-step updates and efficient data auditing.

Excel is not quite a good fit, and while now I know more clearly why Excel is unsuitable and am more committed to a non-Excel solution, we as a team could've clarified the requirements with Milair earlier.
History is repeating itself for sure, but at least this time it's only just over a week into the project.
The rest of the week was split on MySQL database design, stored procedures, triggers, and implementing SOLID in C#.
So many new things to learn and I find myself incredibly pumped again to dive in and explore.
Plus, since I know that these tools will solve Milair's problems and allow me to contribute to the team's effort, my motivation has rebounded quite a bit.
To be honest, I was feeling at a rather low point even before joining the team.
I knew it was going to be non-web based.
I knew it was C# instead of JavaScript, which is the language I wish to invest in.
I never pushed for a web-based solution, but deep down in my mind I still feel like there's no good reason for me to step out of my comfort zone, like really stepping out of it.
After all, if I already know the tools (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Node), why should I learn their C# equivalents?
Should I spend time sharpening and deepening what I already know rather than dabbling in a bunch of similar but not quite tools?
While I certainly did explore new things in the 2nd project, I was still holding onto JavaScript all the way despite learning new libraries and concepts.
It is hard to let go of this feeling of assurance and ease, and this certainly has made me feel discouraged to really step into the Microsoft's world.
After all, I've made the decision to apply for non-C# jobs, at least in the short term.
In a sense, I was being selfish when I pushed for Excel.
While I didn't do it entirely to avoid C#, the motive is there.
And no matter the result, I think that move sort of opens a tiny crack in my relationship with my team.
To be fair, they were being very diplomatic (as Kiwis are) and we did come to a compromise.
But as blindly as I've avoided learning C#, I think we've never really had a discussion as to why C# is the best tool for the job, technically speaking.
But again, none of us are experts, and we're still driven mostly by personal learning goals and aspirations.
It's ironic that my beef with them actually stems from the same ground.
We both want to learn what we think we should learn, and neither side is willing to give it up completely, or even make a compromise.
I suppose the same thing will happen later.
People are factors that you don't really have control over.
It might be your SHIFT teammates today, but it could be other people that make decisions for you later:  your team lead, a senior developer, the company, etc.
The key is to empathize with others and to make the most out of it on your own.
It is not just about negotiating with others, but also with yourself.
So I'm glad I did that.
C# has so many things to teach me about programming itself and even thought I've just begun my journey I've already seen how it helps me reflect upon what I already know.
For example, since JavaScript is event-driven, I didn't quite have the chance to understand or apply SOLID principles in my code explicitly.
But since the C# community is quite adamant about conventions and best practices, I can see how really comprehending SOLID in a clear context can help me write better code in JavaScript.

In a nutshell, another big lesson I learn is that I've made the typical mistake of newcomers, who are easily enamored and swayed by their first encounters with a tool, a concept, even a person, really.
And once you're deep into the woods, it's hard to step out of it and realize there's so much more.
It was a hard lesson and a bit of a cliche, but I learn again to appreciate programming as patterns and principles rather than concrete implementations.
And that's quite comforting when you think of it.
No matter what you're learning, it will improve whatever you already know.
You can be more critical and keep a healthy distance between you and your beloved tools, allowing you to be more conscious of other human variables at play.
At the end of the day, I think I have somehow managed to scope my expectations as I said last week.
And really scoping is not just about narrowing, but also about heading into a new direction that allows you to see the forest beyond the trees.
For this week, I'm hoping to finalize my database schemas and start writing and testing stored procedures as requested by the UI.
Hopefully this will allow me to integrate into the team more and start helping each other out.
My C# is too basic at the moment, but I'm making good progress and I can already see plenty of refactoring that can be done in our current code base.
I think as a team we will really flesh out the software design this week as well, since everyone has just only started to pick up C# except for Bibi, so hopefully we'll come up with a solid plan.
Thank you for reading.
Overall
